ECOMMERCE MERN AWS DEPLOYMENT STEPS
PROJECT ALREADY DOWNLOADED IN DOWNLOADS

Use this on Ubuntu PC during practical exam.

Before starting, keep ready:
1. EC2 public IP
2. .pem key file
3. Project folder ecommerce-mern already present in Downloads
4. EC2 instance must be running
5. EC2 Security Group must allow:
   SSH  port 22  from My IP or 0.0.0.0/0
   HTTP port 80  from 0.0.0.0/0

Example:
Key file: website-key.pem
Project folder: ecommerce-mern
EC2 user: ubuntu
Public IP: YOUR_EC2_PUBLIC_IP


STEP 1: Open terminal on Ubuntu PC

Go to Downloads:

cd ~/Downloads

Check files:

ls

You should see:

website-key.pem
ecommerce-mern


STEP 2: Give permission to key file

chmod 400 website-key.pem


STEP 3: Check project folder

cd ~/Downloads/ecommerce-mern
ls

You should see:

package.json
package-lock.json
server.js
public

Check frontend file:

ls public

You should see:

index.html


STEP 4: Upload project folder to EC2

Go back to Downloads:

cd ~/Downloads

Upload complete project folder:

scp -i website-key.pem -r ecommerce-mern ubuntu@YOUR_EC2_PUBLIC_IP:/home/ubuntu/

Example:

scp -i website-key.pem -r ecommerce-mern ubuntu@3.91.30.11:/home/ubuntu/


STEP 5: Connect to EC2 instance

ssh -i website-key.pem ubuntu@YOUR_EC2_PUBLIC_IP

Example:

ssh -i website-key.pem ubuntu@3.91.30.11


STEP 6: Update Ubuntu packages on EC2

sudo apt update


STEP 7: Install required software

sudo apt install nodejs npm nginx docker.io -y


STEP 8: Start Docker

sudo systemctl enable docker
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo usermod -aG docker ubuntu


STEP 9: Logout and login again for Docker permission

exit

Login again from Ubuntu PC:

cd ~/Downloads
ssh -i website-key.pem ubuntu@YOUR_EC2_PUBLIC_IP


STEP 10: Go to project folder on EC2

cd /home/ubuntu/ecommerce-mern


STEP 11: Check project files on EC2

ls

You should see:

package.json
package-lock.json
server.js
public


STEP 12: Start MongoDB using Docker

docker rm -f ecommerce-mongo 2>/dev/null

docker run -d --name ecommerce-mongo -p 127.0.0.1:27017:27017 -v ecommerce_mongo_data:/data/db mongo:7


STEP 13: Check MongoDB container

docker ps

You should see:

ecommerce-mongo


STEP 14: Install Node dependencies

cd /home/ubuntu/ecommerce-mern
npm install


STEP 15: Test application manually

node server.js

Expected output:

Server running on port 5000
MongoDB connected successfully
Sample products inserted

Stop server:

CTRL + C


STEP 16: Install PM2

sudo npm install -g pm2


STEP 17: Start app using PM2

pm2 delete ecommerce-app 2>/dev/null
pm2 start server.js --name ecommerce-app
pm2 save
pm2 startup


STEP 18: Run PM2 startup command if shown

After pm2 startup, it may show one command starting with:

sudo env PATH=...

Copy that full command and run it once.

Example:

sudo env PATH=$PATH:/usr/bin pm2 startup systemd -u ubuntu --hp /home/ubuntu

Then run:

pm2 save


STEP 19: Check app status

pm2 status

You should see:

ecommerce-app online


STEP 20: Test backend locally on EC2

curl http://localhost:5000

If HTML code appears, app is working.

Test products API:

curl http://localhost:5000/api/products

You should see product data.


STEP 21: Configure Nginx

sudo rm -f /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default
sudo rm -f /etc/nginx/sites-available/ecommerce


STEP 22: Create Nginx reverse proxy config

sudo tee /etc/nginx/sites-available/ecommerce > /dev/null <<'EOF'
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name _;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;

        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
        proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
        proxy_set_header Host $host;

        proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
    }
}
EOF


STEP 23: Enable Nginx config

sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/ecommerce /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/ecommerce


STEP 24: Test Nginx config

sudo nginx -t

Expected output:

syntax is ok
test is successful


STEP 25: Restart Nginx

sudo systemctl restart nginx


STEP 26: Check Nginx status

sudo systemctl status nginx

If it shows active running, press:

q


STEP 27: Allow firewall if active

sudo ufw allow 22
sudo ufw allow 80
sudo ufw status

If UFW status is inactive, no problem.


STEP 28: Open website in browser

http://YOUR_EC2_PUBLIC_IP

Example:

http://3.91.30.11


